	<key>readme</key>
	<string># Mute Discord

Mute Discord with a global hotkey without granting the app ‘Input Monitoring’ permission.

## Usage

Mute and unmute discord without having to give it Input Monitoring permissions via the `mute` keyword. Discord will be brought to the front, muted, then switched to the previous app.

![Muting Discord](images/mute.png)

Configure the Hotkey for faster triggering.

#### Controlling How to Activate Discord

If you mute/unmute Discord from a full-screen app, the workflow might fail or won’t switch back to the previous app afterwards. If that happens, choose another method to activate Discord.

**Methods of Activating Discord:**

- **Method A (Yellow):** Switch between apps using the ⌘↹ shortcut. This method could be unstable if the shortcut doesn’t bring Discord up on time.
- **Method B (Blue):** Default method. Switch back to Discord using the Open Apps Automation Task provided by Alfred.
- **Method C (Red):** Similar to Method B, but it tries activating Discord up to 5 times before giving up. This is useful for long switch animations when triggering the workflow in a full-screen app.

#### Note

*The Discord macOS app has a default mute hotkey of ⌘⇧M, so you don’t need this workflow to mute Discord.*

*However, to use a global hotkey, you must grant the Discord app input monitoring permissions in System Settings. This permission is required (but is not prompted for) to record your custom hotkey. Worse still, the other default hotkeys become global once the permission is granted and cannot be disabled. I wasn’t comfortable giving Discord that permission just to use a global hotkey, so I created this workflow.*</string>
